Student clustering based on the regularity of study indicators

First, read in the computed indicators:

  • number of active days per week
  • SD and entropy of active days per week
  • median time gap between consecutive active days
## load active days per week, SD and entropy 
weekly.counts <- read.csv("Intermediate_results/regularity_of_study/weekly_counts_of_daily_logins_w2-13.csv")
weekly.counts <- weekly.counts %>%
  select(user_id, W2_cnt:W13_cnt, weekly_cnt_sd, weekly_entropy)
#str(weekly.counts)
## load also data about time gaps between consecutive active days
time.gaps <- read.csv("Intermediate_results/regularity_of_study/gaps_between_consecutive_logins_w2-13.csv")
## mean and SD are not very meaningful since only 2% of students have normally distributed time gaps
time.gaps <- time.gaps %>% select(user_id, median_gap)
## merge the indictors
counts <- merge(x = weekly.counts, y = time.gaps, by = 'user_id', all = T)
str(counts)

Read in students exam scores:

exam.scores <- read.csv(file = "Intermediate_results/exam_scores_with_student_ids.csv")
# remove email data
exam.scores <- exam.scores %>% select(-2)
str(exam.scores)
'data.frame':   491 obs. of  3 variables:
 $ USER_ID  : int  NA 1446 961 866 937 734 1077 953 852 932 ...

Merge indicators with exam scores

counts_and_scores <- merge(x = counts, y = exam.scores, 
                           by.x = 'user_id', by.y = 'USER_ID',
                           all.x = T, all.y = F)
#summary(counts_and_scores)
counts_and_scores <- counts_and_scores %>% filter( is.na(SC_FE_TOT)==FALSE )

Check for normality of variables

apply(counts_and_scores[,-1], 2, shapiro.test)

Except for tot_cnt, no other variable is normally distributed -> use Spearman corr.

Use the ggcorr f. for computing and plotting the correlations among variables

source("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/briatte/ggcorr/master/ggcorr.R")
ggcorr(counts_and_scores[,-c(1,17)], method = c("complete","spearman"), 
       #      geom = "circle", min_size = 0, max_size = 15,
       label = TRUE, label_size = 3.5,
       hjust = 0.85, size = 4, layout.exp = 1)

Relatively low correlations between the indicators and the final exam score (SC_FE_TOT).

Check for zero or near-zero variance predictors

## using the nearZeroVar f. from caret:
## https://topepo.github.io/caret/pre-processing.html#zero--and-near-zero-variance-predictors
nzv <- nearZeroVar(counts_and_scores[,-1], saveMetrics= TRUE)
nzv

None has near-zero variance.

Check for outliers:

outliers <- apply(counts_and_scores[,-c(1,17,18)], 2, function(x) length(boxplot.stats(x)$out))
outliers <- outliers[outliers>0]
sort(outliers, decreasing = T)
        W3_cnt weekly_entropy     median_gap        W13_cnt  weekly_cnt_sd 
            74             33             29              6              6

Look more closely at variables with large number of outliers

table(counts_and_scores$W3_cnt)
sort(boxplot.stats(counts_and_scores$W3_cnt)$out)
summary(counts_and_scores$weekly_entropy)
sort(boxplot.stats(counts_and_scores$weekly_entropy)$out)
summary(counts_and_scores$median_gap)
sort(boxplot.stats(counts_and_scores$median_gap)$out)

Use Winsorizing to replace the extreme values with less extreme ones

vars_to_winsorize <- counts_and_scores %>%
  select(one_of(names(outliers)))
winsorized_data_v1 <- data.frame(apply(vars_to_winsorize, 2, winsor1, fraction=0.07))

apply(winsorized_data_v1, 2, function(x) length(boxplot.stats(x)$out))
summary(winsorized_data_v1)
#winsorized_data_v2 <- data.frame(apply(vars_to_winsorize, 2, winsor2))
#apply(winsorized_data_v2, 2, function(x) length(boxplot.stats(x)$out))
#summary(winsorized_data_v2)

Except for W3 counts, all other outliers are resolved.

Merge winsorized variables with the other variables

features <- counts_and_scores %>%
  select(-one_of(names(outliers))) %>%
  select(-c(SC_MT_TOT, SC_FE_TOT)) %>%
  cbind(winsorized_data_v1)
# change the order of variables, to make it easier for later interpretation
features <- features %>% select(1,2,12,3:11,13:16)

Remove weekly_cnt_sd from the feature set since it has zero correlation with the final exam score.

features <- features %>% select(-weekly_cnt_sd)

Scale feature values; since outliers have been removed, normalization can be used

summary(features[,-1])
f.scaled <- data.frame(apply(features[,-1], 2, normalize.feature ))
summary(f.scaled)
f.scaled <- data.frame(cbind(user_id=features$user_id, f.scaled))

Do the clustering

Hierarchical clustering:

hc <- do.hclustering(f.scaled[,-1], 'ward.D2')

3 or 4 seem to be the best options

## examine various cluster models
clusters <- sapply(3:8, function(ncl) table(cutree(hc, k = ncl)))
names(clusters) <- c(3:8)
